00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:14.860
at Horizon 2020 don't
go only at the--

00:37:14.860 --> 00:37:17.290
under the obvious heading
which would be inclusive

00:37:17.290 --> 00:37:20.880
and reflective societies where
there is a lot of research

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:24.220
and opportunities for cultural
heritage research but also

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:27.010
under other areas because
under other areas also you will

00:37:27.010 --> 00:37:29.310
find opportunities.

00:37:30.880 --> 00:37:35.230
And then I want to-- sorry,
maybe just before I come

00:37:35.230 --> 00:37:40.140
on that, I should indicate.

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:42.960
These projects under
these societal challenges,

00:37:42.960 --> 00:37:45.610
they're always collaborative
research project.

00:37:45.610 --> 00:37:49.920
So they almost always must have
at least three European partners

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:52.470
from three different
European countries.

00:37:54.740 --> 00:37:56.700
They can however include partners

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.330
from any other part
of the world also.

00:38:00.330 --> 00:38:03.180
Generally if these partners
come from developing countries,

00:38:03.180 --> 00:38:09.570
such as Africa and we do actually
quite a lot of work with Africa

00:38:09.570 --> 00:38:12.760
or some of the less
developed countries,

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:16.000
for example in Latin America.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.240
If the projects include
partners from those countries,

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:23.420
the European Union will fund fully
the participation of those partners

00:38:23.420 --> 00:38:26.050
if the project is selected.

00:38:26.050 --> 00:38:27.750
For countries such
as the United States,

00:38:27.750 --> 00:38:29.710
which is an industrialized country,

00:38:29.710 --> 00:38:32.820
the European Union generally
does not fund the participation

00:38:32.820 --> 00:38:34.560
of the American partner.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:38.870
The American partner is expected to
bring their own funds to the table.

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:40.910
But what's the advantage
for the American partner?

00:38:40.910 --> 00:38:44.130
Well, the advantage of course for
the American partner is the access

00:38:44.130 --> 00:38:47.200
to all of the work that is being
done by the other partners,

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:54.550
and it's the access to that
network, access to the new results

00:38:54.550 --> 00:38:57.690
that are being produced
but also being part

00:38:57.690 --> 00:39:00.010
of the new results that
are being produced.

00:39:00.010 --> 00:39:01.310
So it's really an opportunity

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:03.880
for international cooperation
at a very high level.

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:06.830
So therefore that's why we say
Horizon 2020 is open to the world

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:12.440
and we really encourage and
like to have American partners.

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:16.310
So any Europeans in the
audience who are thinking

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:21.090
of preparing Horizon 2020 projects
to submit, please do remember

00:39:21.090 --> 00:39:25.560 position:56%
that American partners are extremely
welcome and any Americans who are

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:28.990
in the audience who have good ideas
for research projects and would

00:39:28.990 --> 00:39:32.740
like to internationalize them,
then please don't hesitate to speak

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:35.580
with some European partners
and look at the opportunities

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:39.510
that Horizon 2020 might
be able to provide to you.

00:39:39.510 --> 00:39:44.900
Another aspect I would like to
mention regarding Horizon 2020

00:39:44.900 --> 00:39:46.500
that you may or may not be familiar

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:51.380
with are the European
Research Council grants.

00:39:51.380 --> 00:40:00.140
And the European Research
Council grants are relatively new

00:40:00.140 --> 00:40:03.420
in European research funding terms.

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:06.290
Actually 2017 will be
the 10th anniversary

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:08.140
of the European Research Council.

00:40:08.140 --> 00:40:11.690
And since the European
Research Council was set up,

00:40:11.690 --> 00:40:19.860
it has been funding individual
investigators at a very,

00:40:19.860 --> 00:40:26.960
very high level with very
prestigious, very generous grants.

00:40:26.960 --> 00:40:29.810
Any researcher from anywhere
in the world can apply

00:40:29.810 --> 00:40:32.910 position:56%
for European Research Council grant.

00:40:35.490 --> 00:40:42.140
One of the stipulations however
is that that person must spend

00:40:42.140 --> 00:40:44.430
at least 50% of their
time in Europe.

00:40:44.430 --> 00:40:46.970
Because the idea of the European
Research Council grants is

00:40:46.970 --> 00:40:50.460
that people will set
up a lab in Europe.

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:52.740
Now, I'll be very brief on this
because I could talk about it

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:54.060
for half a day because it's one

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:56.330
of my favorite topics,
but I'll be very brief.

00:40:56.330 --> 00:40:59.270 position:56%
There are three main types of grant.

00:40:59.270 --> 00:41:02.780
There are grant for-- they're
called Starting Grants.

00:41:02.780 --> 00:41:05.090
Most of the money goes
to starting grants.

00:41:05.090 --> 00:41:07.410
And these are for individuals
who are ready to set

00:41:07.410 --> 00:41:14.830
up their own research
lab for the first time.

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:19.930
The researcher who applies must
nevertheless be able to demonstrate

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:24.010
that they have really
the capacity and the--

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:28.480
really show the potential
to make a difference

00:41:28.480 --> 00:41:31.010
in their chosen area of research.

00:41:31.010 --> 00:41:34.850 position:56%
And what's very important is that
the area of research can be any area

00:41:34.850 --> 00:41:39.810
of research including of course
humanities, cultural heritage

00:41:39.810 --> 00:41:44.750
and the arts, as well as
physics or brain science.

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:46.950
It can be anything.

00:41:46.950 --> 00:41:49.190
Then we have a-- there's
a second type of grant

00:41:49.190 --> 00:41:50.900
which is called the
Consolidator Grant.

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:53.580
The consolidator grants
are for people who are

00:41:53.580 --> 00:41:58.880
at a more advanced stage in their
research career and they have a--

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:04.740
Well, they want to consolidate.

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:07.920
They probably already
have a small lab perhaps.

00:42:07.920 --> 00:42:12.530
They have already a number
of serious publications.

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:15.950
And they have between 7 and
12 years after their PhD.

00:42:15.950 --> 00:42:19.600
And then finally, we
have the Advanced Grants,

00:42:19.600 --> 00:42:24.370
which are far much more senior
researchers who want to come

00:42:24.370 --> 00:42:28.970
and spend some time in-- who want
to develop a research program

00:42:28.970 --> 00:42:31.910
in Europe, set up a lab
or a research group.

00:42:31.910 --> 00:42:34.710
It doesn't have to be a lab, of
course it can be a research group.

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:37.890
And there also, you can see
that it's very generous.

00:42:37.890 --> 00:42:40.590
And you can see that they're very
generous grants for individuals.

00:42:40.590 --> 00:42:43.450
And the idea is that they
set up a research group.

00:42:43.450 --> 00:42:47.240
Now, I said they have to spend at
least 50% of their time in Europe,

00:42:47.240 --> 00:42:50.460
generally the starting grants will
spend most of their time in Europe.

00:42:50.460 --> 00:42:53.240
If you're going to set up your
own lab for the first time,

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:55.010
you're not only going
their part time.

00:42:55.010 --> 00:43:01.140
But it's very interesting for a
consolidator or in advanced grant

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:05.370
to know that you don't have to
spend all of your time in Europe.

00:43:05.370 --> 00:43:09.140
So therefore, if you have a
position here at a university

00:43:09.140 --> 00:43:13.610
and that university allows you
to, you can go and, you know,

00:43:13.610 --> 00:43:16.580
open a new lab or set up
a new group in Europe.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:18.790
And in particular, the
advanced grants you only need

00:43:18.790 --> 00:43:22.070
to just spend 30% of
your time in Europe.

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:23.680
What's also interesting
I would like to say

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:27.860
about this European Research
Council grants is that of course,

00:43:27.860 --> 00:43:30.680
once you set up your research
group or once the person

00:43:30.680 --> 00:43:35.290
who was selected sets up their
research group, they can have--

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:38.180
they can staff their
group with researchers

00:43:38.180 --> 00:43:40.010
from anywhere in the world.

00:43:40.010 --> 00:43:42.450
So this is also an
interesting opportunity.

00:43:42.450 --> 00:43:44.140
They have to publish
all of those posts.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:45.790
Well, they publish
most of those posts

00:43:45.790 --> 00:43:47.880
and those posts are all advertised.

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:52.760
So a person who is interested
in coming to Europe to work

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:57.680
in cultural heritage could
for example apply for a grant,

00:43:57.680 --> 00:44:01.700
which is very prestigious
if you are selected.

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:05.910
But there's also the option to
look at posts that are published

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:09.090
in the research groups of people
who have already gotten a grant.

00:44:09.090 --> 00:44:10.390
So therefore all you
have to do is apply

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:12.450
for a job rather than
apply for a grant.

00:44:12.450 --> 00:44:14.290
So this is also an option.

00:44:14.290 --> 00:44:16.530
And I would specifically
like to mention that all

00:44:16.530 --> 00:44:23.530
of the European Research Council
grantees also have the possibility

00:44:23.530 --> 00:44:30.570
to host a temporary, on a temporary
basis from maybe three months

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:33.950
to nine moths, an NSF-founded
career grantee.

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:36.200
Because there's a special
implementing arrangement

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:38.090
between the National
Science Foundation

00:44:38.090 --> 00:44:42.130
and the European Research
Council, which allows--

00:44:42.130 --> 00:44:47.890
so the NSF continues to support
the US researcher and the--

00:44:47.890 --> 00:44:51.000
and pay their travel to Europe.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:54.780
And the European Research
Council grantee--

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:58.550
investigator supports them
while they're in Europe.

00:44:58.550 --> 00:45:03.230
So you know, give some daily
allowance, so to speak.

00:45:03.230 --> 00:45:05.470
So I just wanted to talk
there about the opportunities

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:09.260
that the European Research
Council offers.

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:13.490
There's also another
opportunity for individuals,

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:15.290
which is the Marie
Curie Fellowships.

00:45:15.290 --> 00:45:23.310
The Marie Curie Fellowships we tend
to say are more on-- more upstream.

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:26.380 position:56%
So therefore, they tend to be people
who are just going to do a postdoc.

00:45:26.380 --> 00:45:29.040
If you are applying for a Marie
Curie Fellowship, you wouldn't be

00:45:29.040 --> 00:45:31.970
at the same stage as if you
were applying for an ERC grant.

00:45:31.970 --> 00:45:37.700
But a Marie Curie Fellowship,
again, very well paid.

00:45:37.700 --> 00:45:39.930
It's a job.

00:45:39.930 --> 00:45:42.550
It's not just a grant.

00:45:42.550 --> 00:45:46.230
And these fellowships are
interesting and I don't have a lot

00:45:46.230 --> 00:45:48.220
of time, so I won't spend
a lot of time on it.

00:45:48.220 --> 00:45:51.230
But the Marie Curie Fellowships
are very interesting firstly

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:56.830
because anybody in the
United States can apply

00:45:56.830 --> 00:46:01.020
for a Marie Curie Fellowship
to go and work in Europe.

00:46:01.020 --> 00:46:04.000
So, if for example, you hear
in the next couple of days

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:08.140
about some wonderful projects
that would be able to host you

00:46:08.140 --> 00:46:12.840
as an American, you can apply for
the Marie Curie Fellowship to come

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:17.430
to Europe for two years, and
you would get paid for that.

00:46:17.430 --> 00:46:20.670
Also you get traveling allowance,
you get language training.

00:46:20.670 --> 00:46:22.990
So it's very, very--
they're very nice.

00:46:22.990 --> 00:46:25.200
It's a very nice scheme.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:28.910
Also very interestingly, it
works in the opposite direction.

00:46:28.910 --> 00:46:31.370
So if there's a European who
is interested to come to work

00:46:31.370 --> 00:46:35.100
in the United States in perhaps
one of your groups for a while,

00:46:35.100 --> 00:46:38.740
they have the opportunity to apply
for a Marie Curie Fellowship also

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:40.320
to go to the United States.

00:46:40.320 --> 00:46:42.860
Well, they can go anywhere in
the world, but since I'm here

00:46:42.860 --> 00:46:44.730
in America, I'm going to
talk about the opportunity

00:46:44.730 --> 00:46:46.120
to come to the United States.

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:48.850 position:56%
So therefore this is also
something that's interesting for you

00:46:48.850 --> 00:46:52.640 position:56%
to be aware of, if for example you
have a European who is saying, "God,

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:55.290
I really like to come
but I don't know how I"--

00:46:55.290 --> 00:46:57.660
you don't maybe have
the funding for them.

00:46:57.660 --> 00:46:59.060
It's really interesting
because basically

00:46:59.060 --> 00:47:03.390
for the American side,
it's a free postdoc.

00:47:03.390 --> 00:47:06.740
For the European side,
what's very interesting is

00:47:06.740 --> 00:47:09.410
that the European postdoc who
gets the opportunity to come

00:47:09.410 --> 00:47:12.720
to America must return to
Europe for at least one year.

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:14.780
So therefore, Europe
benefits also from what

00:47:14.780 --> 00:47:16.890
that person learns
in the United States.

00:47:16.890 --> 00:47:19.690
So it's really a win-win situation.

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:26.900
Well, I think I touched
on this a little bit.

00:47:26.900 --> 00:47:30.300
Why would American researchers
be interested to participate

00:47:30.300 --> 00:47:32.350
in Horizon 2020 project,

00:47:32.350 --> 00:47:34.390
particularly in the
collaborative research projects?

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:38.280 position:56%
Obviously, there's the access to
expertise, equipment and facilities,

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:40.720
economies of scale and
scope when you're dealing

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:44.860
with very large projects,
increased research quality,

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:50.150 position:56%
greater impact efficiency and speed,
developing networks and alliances

00:47:50.150 --> 00:47:54.640
which of course we all know in
science is very, very important.

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:57.850
Career development opportunities
such as those of the ERC

00:47:57.850 --> 00:48:00.120
and Marie Curie, which
I just mentioned to you.

00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:03.000
And eventually business and
commercialization opportunities

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:08.450
because if you work together and
develop a new means, for example,

00:48:08.450 --> 00:48:12.130
of preserving some particular
type of cultural heritage,

00:48:12.130 --> 00:48:14.300
well maybe it's something
that can be sold to museums

00:48:14.300 --> 00:48:16.920
around the world, for example.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.970
So I think I've gone through
the participation possibilities

00:48:21.970 --> 00:48:26.810
as ERC grantees, as
Marie Curie Fellowships,

00:48:26.810 --> 00:48:28.550
collaborative research projects.

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:33.790
And I also mentioned that
for US partners generally,

00:48:33.790 --> 00:48:36.780
funding is not available,

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:42.010
but nevertheless there
are a lot of advantages.

00:48:42.010 --> 00:48:44.920
Oops, I also briefly touched
on the rules for participation.

00:48:44.920 --> 00:48:47.940
There have to be at least
three European parties

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:49.710 position:56%
in a collaborative research project.

00:48:49.710 --> 00:48:51.420
In the collaborative
research project.

00:48:51.420 --> 00:48:56.120
Of course, for the Marie Curie
Fellowships, all you need in order

00:48:56.120 --> 00:48:57.990
to apply for Marie Curie
Fellowship is you need

00:48:57.990 --> 00:49:01.520
to have a really good project
idea and a host institution,

00:49:01.520 --> 00:49:04.500
whether you're going to Europe
or going to the United States.

00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:07.390
And of course, these are
all very competitive.

00:49:07.390 --> 00:49:09.860
But nevertheless, as
we say in Ireland,

00:49:09.860 --> 00:49:11.160
if you're not in, you can't in.

00:49:11.160 --> 00:49:15.210 position:56%
So therefore you have to, you know,
put your research projects together.

00:49:15.210 --> 00:49:19.010
And likewise with the European
Research Council, again,

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:24.250
